content_chunks.content: The e-course provides an overview of heating, ventilation and air conditioning (HVAC) systems and their control in buildings, focusing on non-residential buildings and their control strategies. The course provides the basic theory of HVAC and automation first. Then, control algorithms applied in different building services are explained and observed in simulation and exemplary buildings. Alternatives and energy efficient solutions are discussed in conclusion.

HVAC control technology for building energy optimization - this course delivers advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning management systems for enhanced building performance and energy efficiency. Technology for indoor climate control includes sophisticated automation principles and building automation systems integration, while heating systems control focuses on Building Management Systems (BMS) optimization for energy consumption reduction. The course introduces ventilation systems control strategies and cooling systems management techniques for comprehensive environmental comfort solutions. Participants gain expertise in HVAC systems fundamentals, automation theory, and energy efficient HVAC solutions implementation using advanced simulation tools. The curriculum covers building management system operations, energy consumption analysis, and control algorithm optimization for non-residential building applications. Students develop skills in IDA ICE simulation software, HVAC system analysis, and control strategy implementation for improved building performance. The course prepares professionals to design, implement, and manage modern HVAC control systems that maximize energy efficiency while maintaining optimal indoor environmental conditions in commercial and institutional buildings.
